buildHistoryToken

public String buildHistoryToken(PlaceRequest request)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Builds a string corresponding to the history token to reveal the specified PlaceRequest. This can be used with a Hyperlink.

Invoking this history token will discard all the place hierarchy, effectively revealing the request as a top-level place. To keep the place hierarchy, see PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(PlaceRequest), PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(PlaceRequest, int) or PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(int).

Specified by:
buildHistoryToken in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
request - The PlaceRequest corresponding to the place for which to build a history token.
Returns:
The history token.
See Also:
PlaceManager.revealPlace(PlaceRequest)

buildRelativeHistoryToken

public String buildRelativeHistoryToken(int level)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Builds a string corresponding to the history token to reveal the specified place from the current place hierarchy.

Examples, suppose the current hierarchy is requestA > requestB > requestC

  • Calling revealRelativePlace(-1) will make a link to requestA > requestB
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(1) will make a link to requestA
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(0) will make a link to requestA > requestB > requestC
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(-3) or less will make a link to ""
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(3) or more will make a link to requestA > requestB > requestC

Specified by:
buildRelativeHistoryToken in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
level - If negative, take back that many elements from the tail of the hierarchy. If positive, keep only that many elements from the head of the hierarchy. Passing 0 makes a link to the current place.
See Also:
PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(int)

buildRelativeHistoryToken

public String buildRelativeHistoryToken(PlaceRequest request)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Builds a string corresponding to the history token to reveal the specified PlaceRequest as a child of the current place hierarchy. Identical to calling PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(PlaceRequest, int) with a level of 0.

To get the history token for revealing as a top-level place, see PlaceManager.buildHistoryToken(com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.proxy.PlaceRequest). To navigate back to a specific place in the hierarchy, see PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(int).

Specified by:

buildRelativeHistoryToken

public String buildRelativeHistoryToken(PlaceRequest request,
                                        int level)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Builds a string corresponding to the history token to reveal the specified PlaceRequest relative to the other places in the current place hierarchy.

To get the history token for revealing as a top-level place, see PlaceManager.buildHistoryToken(com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.proxy.PlaceRequest). To navigate back to a specific place in the hierarchy, see PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(int).

Examples, suppose the current hierarchy is requestA > requestB > requestC

  • Calling buildRelativeHistoryToken(requestD, 0) will make a link to requestA > requestB > requestC > requestD
  • Calling buildRelativeHistoryToken(requestD, -1) will make a link to requestA > requestB > requestD
  • Calling buildRelativeHistoryToken(requestD, 1) will make a link to requestA > requestD
  • Calling buildRelativeHistoryToken(requestD, -3) will make a link to requestD
  • Calling buildRelativeHistoryToken(requestD, 3) will make a link to requestA > requestB > requestC > requestD

Specified by:
buildRelativeHistoryToken in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
request - The PlaceRequest corresponding to the place for which to build a history token.
level - If 0, then simply appends the request to the current page hierarchy. If negative, take back that many elements from the tail of the hierarchy before appending the request. If positive, keep only that many elements from the head of the hierarchy before appending the request.
Returns:
The history token.
See Also:
PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(PlaceRequest, int)

getCurrentTitle

public void getCurrentTitle(SetPlaceTitleHandler handler)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Retrieves the title of the currently displayed place, or null if it doesn't have a title. Same as calling PlaceManager.getTitle(int, SetPlaceTitleHandler) with a level of PlaceManager.getHierarchyDepth()-1.

Instead of returning the title directly, this method accepts a callback and will call SetPlaceTitleHandler.onSetPlaceTitle(java.lang.String) as soon as the title is available. This makes it possible for the user to query the title from the server based on the PlaceRequest parameters, for example.

Specified by:
getCurrentTitle in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
handler - The SetPlaceTitleHandler to invoke when the place title is available. This will be invoked with null if the place doesn't have a title.

getTitle

public void getTitle(int index,
                     SetPlaceTitleHandler handler)
              throws IndexOutOfBoundsException
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Retrieves the title of a specific place within the place hierarchy.

Instead of returning the title directly, this method accepts a callback and will call SetPlaceTitleHandler.onSetPlaceTitle(java.lang.String) as soon as the title is available. This makes it possible for the user to query the title from the server based on the PlaceRequest parameters, for example.

Specified by:
getTitle in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
index - The index of the place for which to get a title, 0 is the top-level class, PlaceManager.getHierarchyDepth()-1 is the current place.
handler - The SetPlaceTitleHandler to invoke when the place title is available. This will be invoked with null if the place doesn't have a title.
Throws:
IndexOutOfBoundsException - If the index is less than 0 or greater or equal to PlaceManager.getHierarchyDepth().

revealErrorPlace

public void revealErrorPlace(String invalidHistoryToken)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Reveals the place to display when a user tries to access an invalid place. This is invoked when the history token was not handled by any place within the application. Application-specific place managers should build a PlaceRequest corresponding to the desired presenter and call PlaceManager.revealPlace(PlaceRequest) with it. The default implementation is simply to call PlaceManager.revealDefaultPlace().

Important! Make sure you build a valid PlaceRequest and that the user has access to it, otherwise you might create an infinite loop.

Specified by:
revealErrorPlace in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
invalidHistoryToken - The history token that was not recognised.

revealPlace

public final void revealPlace(PlaceRequest request)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Programmatically reveals the specified place. This will result in a PlaceRequestInternalEvent being fired.

This discards all the place hierarchy, effectively revealing the request as a top-level place. To keep the place hierarchy, see PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(PlaceRequest), PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(PlaceRequest, int) or PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(int). To reveal an entire place hierarchy, see PlaceManager.revealPlaceHierarchy(java.util.List).

Specified by:
revealPlace in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
request - The PlaceRequest corresponding to the place to reveal.
See Also:
PlaceManager.buildHistoryToken(PlaceRequest)

revealPlaceHierarchy

public final void revealPlaceHierarchy(List<PlaceRequest> placeRequestHierarchy)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Programmatically reveals the specified hierarchy of places place. This will result in a PlaceRequestInternalEvent being fired.

This discards all the place hierarchy, replacing it with the specified place hierarchy. To keep the place hierarchy, see PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(PlaceRequest), PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(PlaceRequest, int) or PlaceManager.revealRelativePlace(int). To reveal a single Place instead of a hierarchy, see PlaceManager.revealPlace(com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.proxy.PlaceRequest).

Specified by:
revealPlaceHierarchy in interface PlaceManager

revealRelativePlace

public void revealRelativePlace(int level)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Programmatically reveals the specified place from the current place hierarchy. This will result in a PlaceRequestInternalEvent being fired.

Examples, suppose the current hierarchy is requestA > requestB > requestC

  • Calling revealRelativePlace(-1) makes it requestA > requestB
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(1) makes it requestA
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(0) makes it requestA > requestB > requestC
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(-3) or less calls PlaceManager.revealDefaultPlace()
  • Calling revealRelativePlace(3) or more makes it requestA > requestB > requestC

Specified by:
revealRelativePlace in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
level - If negative, take back that many elements from the tail of the hierarchy. If positive, keep only that many elements from the head of the hierarchy. Passing 0 reveals the current place.
See Also:
PlaceManager.buildRelativeHistoryToken(int)

revealUnauthorizedPlace

public void revealUnauthorizedPlace(String unauthorizedHistoryToken)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Reveals the place to display when a user has been refused the access to a specific place. This is invoked when the history token is valid but the corresponding place's Place.canReveal() returned false. Application-specific place managers should build a PlaceRequest corresponding to the desired presenter and call PlaceManager.revealPlace(PlaceRequest) with it. The default implementation is simply to call PlaceManager.revealErrorPlace(String).

Important! Make sure you build a valid PlaceRequest and that the user has access to it, otherwise you might create an infinite loop.

Specified by:
revealUnauthorizedPlace in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
unauthorizedHistoryToken - The history token that was not authorized.

setOnLeaveConfirmation

public final void setOnLeaveConfirmation(String question)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Sets the question that will be displayed whenever the user tries to navigate away from the current page. Navigating away can happen either occur by changing the program state (the history token), by entering an external URL or by closing the window. All cases will be handled.

If the user indicates that he doesn't accept the navigation, then the navigation will be cancelled, NavigationRefusedEvent will be triggered and the current page will remain.

Specified by:
setOnLeaveConfirmation in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
question - The question to display. Pass null to accept navigation directly, without asking a question.

unlock

public void unlock()
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Resets the navigation lock if it is currently set. You should usually not call this directly, instead it is meant to be used with presenters that use manual reveal via ProxyPlace.manualReveal(com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.Presenter) and ProxyPlace.manualRevealFailed().

Specified by:
unlock in interface PlaceManager
See Also:
Presenter.useManualReveal(), ProxyPlace.manualReveal(com.gwtplatform.mvp.client.Presenter), ProxyPlace.manualRevealFailed()

updateHistory

public void updateHistory(PlaceRequest request)
Description copied from interface: PlaceManager
Updates History, without firing a ValueChangeEvent. Only the last PlaceRequest of the place request hierarchy is modified.

This method will only work if the passed PlaceRequest has the same name token as the current place request (see PlaceManager.getCurrentPlaceRequest().

This method causes a new token to be added to the browser history, affecting the behavior of the browser's back button.

Specified by:
updateHistory in interface PlaceManager
Parameters:
request - The PlaceRequest to display in the updated history.
